Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sknaseerhussain/logistic-regression-for-telecom-churn

This data set contains customer data from a telecom company and the goal is to identify variables that could affect churning in order to help retain customers.

Target variable: Churn
Churn = 1 (likely to leave the provider)
Churn = 0 (will remain with the provider)

Loading data, turning target variable into binary

telecom <- readr::read_csv(
  file = "/Users/thienpham/Data Mining/data/telecom.csv",
  col_types = "ccccccccccccccccccccc",
) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    target = as.numeric(Churn == "Yes")       
)
telecom <- as.data.frame(telecom)

Visualizing target variable

telecom_plot <- telecom %>%
  dplyr::group_by(Churn) %>%                                                 
  dplyr::summarise(n = dplyr::n()) %>%                                       
  dplyr::ungroup() %>%                                                       
  dplyr::mutate(percent = round(100*n/sum(n)),label = paste0(n,", ",percent,"%")) %>%   # shows percentage 
  as.data.frame()

ggplot(telecom_plot) + 
  aes(x = Churn,y = n,fill = Churn,label = label) + 
  geom_col() + 
  geom_text(position = position_stack(0.5)) +
  labs(
    title = "Bar plot of target variable: Churn",
    caption = "Yes = likely to leave the provider, No = will remain with the provider"
  )

Converting categorical predictors to factors with levels ordered by frequency

v_categorical <- names(categorical)
# Name of categorical predictors
v_categorical <- v_categorical[v_categorical != "Churn"]

for(j in v_categorical) telecom[,j] <- forcats::fct_infreq(
  f = telecom[,j]
)

Sorting categorical predictors by Chi-squared test p-value

v_categorical <- names(sort(sapply( 
  X = v_categorical,
  FUN = function(j) chisq.test(
    x = table(telecom[,c("Churn",j)])
  )$p.value
)))

Visualizing categorical predictors with binary target variable

v_color <- c(
  "red","forestgreen","skyblue"
)
names(v_color) <- c(
  "(0,33]","(33,67]","(67,100]"    # creates 3 color categories corresponding to 3 interval range
)


for(j in v_categorical){                    # goes through for each predictor variable
  telecom_plot <- telecom %>%
    dplyr::select_("Churn",j) %>%           # selects only the target variable and jth predictor variable
    dplyr::group_by_("Churn",j) %>%         # then groups by levels of the target variable then the predictor variable
    dplyr::summarise(n = dplyr::n()) %>%    # then sums up each combination
    dplyr::group_by_(j) %>%                 # now group by the predictor variable, then calculates percentage
    dplyr::mutate(percent = round(100*n/sum(n)),label = paste0(n,"\n",percent,"%"),percent = cut(percent,breaks = c(0,33,67,100)))
  
  
  p <- ggplot(telecom_plot) + 
    aes_string(x = j) +
    aes(y = Churn,label = label) + 
    geom_point(aes(size = n,color = percent)) +
    geom_text() + 
    scale_size_area(max_size = 20) + 
    scale_color_manual(values = v_color) + 
    theme_bw() + 
    labs(
      title = paste0("Bubble plot of Churn by ",j),
      subtitle = "Large red and blue bubbles are better for predictor variables.",
      caption = paste0(
        "Chi-squared test p-value: ",round(chisq.test(table(telecom[,c("Churn",j)]))$p.value,22)
      )
    )
  plot(
    x = p
  )
}

Based on the plots and the ordering by on chi squared p value, it seems that OnlineSecurity has the most association with Churning. From an initial glance, we can automatically associate having online security with not churning.

Binning nominal levels into binary

for(j in v_categorical){
  v_table <- sort(
    x = table(
      x = telecom[,j]
    ),
    decreasing = TRUE
  )
  telecom[,j] <- as.numeric(
    x = telecom[,j] == names(v_table)[1]
  )
  v_table <- unclass(
    x = v_table
  )
  telecom_churn <- data.frame(
    level = names(v_table),
    n = v_table,
    proportion = prop.table(v_table)
  )
  print(
    x = "---------------------------------------------------------------------"
  )
  print(
    x = j
  )
  print(
    x = telecom_churn
  )
}

After testing out both binning by conditional mean and by frequency, we stuck with frequency since both gave the same results. All of the categorical predictors had a min of 0 and a max of 1. Most of the variables had a mean within 1/3 and 2/3, anything outside was already a 2 level variable so no further binning was necessary.

Converting numeric columns back to numbers

v_numeric <- c(
  "tenure","MonthlyCharges","TotalCharges"
)
for(j in v_numeric) telecom[,j] <- as.numeric(
  x = telecom[,j]
)

Capping extreme numeric values to prevents outliers from pulling model away from the rest of the data

# Capping extreme values outside of the 99 percentile to the highest capped value at 99 percentile.
for(j in v_numeric){
  v_cutoffs <- quantile(
    x = telecom[,j],
    probs = c(
      0.01,0.99
    ),
    na.rm = TRUE
  )
  telecom[telecom[,j] < v_cutoffs[1] & !is.na(telecom[,j] < v_cutoffs[1]),j] <- v_cutoffs[1]
  telecom[v_cutoffs[2] < telecom[,j] & !is.na(v_cutoffs[2] < telecom[,j]),j] <- v_cutoffs[2]
}

Applying transformations to numeric predictors

After testing out different transformations, the BoxCox method yielded the most normal distribution. While the other methods like YeoJohnson and exponential did improve the distribution, the improvements were not as substantial.

telecom$Bin <- cut_number(  
  x = telecom$tenure,
  n = 3,
  closed = "left"
)
telecom %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(tenure)) %>%  
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = tenure,fill = Bin) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_bw() +
  #coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,50000)) +
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of pre transformed tenure",
  )
